## PART 4 — STANDALONE PAGES

### 4.1 Universal Back Button Pattern (ALL standalone pages)

Every standalone page must have this sticky topnav:
```html
<nav class="topnav">
  <button class="back-btn" onclick="window.location='index.html'">← Back</button>
  <div class="nav-crumb">portfolio / section / <span>page-name</span></div>
  <div class="nav-right">
    <div class="nav-pill">LABEL 1</div>
    <div class="nav-pill">LABEL 2</div>
  </div>
</nav>
```

**NEVER use `history.back()` or `window.history.length` checks** — always use `window.location='index.html'` for reliability.

For pages that can be reached from multiple entry points (like an IAM reference page), use smart referrer detection:
```javascript
var ref = document.referrer;
var dest = 'index.html';
if (ref) {
  var filename = ref.split('/').pop().split('?')[0];
  dest = filename || 'index.html';
}
document.getElementById('backBtn').onclick = () => window.location = dest;
```

### 4.2 Sidebar + Content Layout (Skills, Industry pages)

```css
.layout {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: 220px 1fr;
  min-height: calc(100vh - 54px);
}
.sidebar {
  position: sticky; top: 54px;
  height: calc(100vh - 54px);
  overflow-y: auto;
  background: var(--surface);
  border-right: 1px solid var(--border);
}
```

**CRITICAL**: Name all scroll functions something other than `scrollTo` — that name conflicts with the browser's native `window.scrollTo(x,y)` API and will silently break all sidebar links. Use `scrollToSection(id)` instead:

```javascript
// WRONG — breaks silently:
function scrollTo(id) { ... }

// CORRECT:
function scrollToSection(id) {
  const el = document.getElementById(id);
  if (el) el.scrollIntoView({ behavior: 'smooth', block: 'start' });
}
```

